<file path="docs/deployment.md">
  1: # Deployment Guide
  2: 
  3: This guide covers deploying the Google Calendar MCP Server for remote access via HTTP transport.
  4: 
  5: ## Transport Modes
  6: 
  7: ### stdio Transport (Default)
  8: - Local use only
  9: - Direct communication with Claude Desktop
 10: - No network exposure
 11: - Automatic authentication handling
 12: 
 13: ### HTTP Transport
 14: - Remote deployment capable
 15: - Server-Sent Events (SSE) for real-time communication
 16: - Built-in security features
 17: - Suitable for cloud deployment
 18: 
 19: ## HTTP Server Features
 20: 
 21: - ✅ **CORS Support**: Basic cross-origin access support
 22: - ✅ **Health Monitoring**: Basic health check endpoint
 23: - ✅ **Graceful Shutdown**: Proper resource cleanup
 24: - ✅ **Origin Validation**: DNS rebinding protection
 25: 
 26: ## Local HTTP Deployment
 27: 
 28: ### Basic HTTP Server
 29: 
 30: ```bash
 31: # Start on localhost only (default port 3000)
 32: npm run start:http
 33: ```
 34: 
 35: ### Public HTTP Server
 36: 
 37: ```bash
 38: # Listen on all interfaces (0.0.0.0)
 39: npm run start:http:public
 40: ```
 41: 
 42: ### Environment Variables
 43: 
 44: ```bash
 45: PORT=3000                    # Server port
 46: HOST=localhost              # Bind address
 47: TRANSPORT=http              # Transport mode
 48: ```
 49: 
 50: ## Cloud Deployment
 51: 
 52: ### Google Cloud Run
 53: 
 54: ```bash
 55: # Build and push image
 56: gcloud builds submit --tag gcr.io/PROJECT-ID/calendar-mcp
 57: 
 58: # Deploy
 59: gcloud run deploy calendar-mcp \
 60:   --image gcr.io/PROJECT-ID/calendar-mcp \
 61:   --platform managed \
 62:   --region us-central1 \
 63:   --allow-unauthenticated \
 64:   --set-env-vars="TRANSPORT=http"
 65: ```
 66: 
 67: ### AWS ECS
 68: 
 69: 1. Push image to ECR
 70: 2. Create task definition with environment variables
 71: 3. Deploy service with ALB
 72: 
 73: ### Heroku
 74: 
 75: ```bash
 76: # Create app
 77: heroku create your-calendar-mcp
 78: 
 79: # Set buildpack
 80: heroku buildpacks:set heroku/nodejs
 81: 
 82: # Configure
 83: heroku config:set TRANSPORT=http
 84: heroku config:set GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS=./gcp-oauth.keys.json
 85: 
 86: # Deploy
 87: git push heroku main
 88: ```
 89: 
 90: ## Security Configuration
 91: 
 92: ### HTTPS/TLS
 93: 
 94: Always use HTTPS in production:
 95: 
 96: 1. **Behind a Reverse Proxy** (Recommended)
 97:    ```nginx
 98:    server {
 99:        listen 443 ssl;
100:        server_name calendar-mcp.example.com;
101:        
102:        ssl_certificate /path/to/cert.pem;
103:        ssl_certificate_key /path/to/key.pem;
104:        
105:        location / {
106:            proxy_pass http://localhost:3000;
107:            proxy_http_version 1.1;
108:            proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
109:            proxy_set_header Connection '';
110:            proxy_set_header Host $host;
111:            proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
112:        }
113:    }
114:    ```
115: 
116: 2. **Direct TLS** (Not built-in)
117:    For TLS support, use a reverse proxy like nginx or a cloud load balancer with SSL termination.
118: 
119: 
120: ### Authentication Flow
121: 
122: 1. Client connects to HTTP endpoint
123: 2. Server redirects to Google OAuth
124: 3. User authenticates with Google
125: 4. Server stores tokens securely
126: 5. Client receives session token
127: 6. All requests use session token
128: 
129: ## Monitoring
130: 
131: ### Health Checks
132: 
133: ```bash
134: # Health check
135: curl http://localhost:3000/health
136: ```
137: 
138: ### Logging
139: 
140: ```bash
141: # Enable debug logging
142: DEBUG=mcp:* npm run start:http
143: 
144: # JSON logging for production
145: NODE_ENV=production npm run start:http
146: ```
147: 
148: 
149: ## Production Checklist
150: 
151: **OAuth App Setup:**
152: - [ ] **Publish OAuth app to production in Google Cloud Console**
153: - [ ] **Set up proper redirect URIs for your domain**
154: - [ ] **Use production OAuth credentials (not test/development)**
155: - [ ] **Consider submitting for verification to remove user warnings**
156: 
157: **Infrastructure:**
158: - [ ] Use HTTPS/TLS encryption
159: - [ ] Configure reverse proxy for production
160: - [ ] Set up SSL termination
161: - [ ] Set up monitoring/alerting for authentication failures
162: - [ ] Configure log aggregation
163: - [ ] Implement backup strategy for token storage
164: - [ ] Test disaster recovery and re-authentication procedures
165: - [ ] Review security headers
166: - [ ] Enable graceful shutdown
167: 
168: **Note**: The 7-day token expiration is resolved by publishing your OAuth app to production in Google Cloud Console.
169: 
170: ## Troubleshooting
171: 
172: ### Connection Issues
173: - Check firewall rules
174: - Verify CORS configuration
175: - Test with curl first
176: 
177: ### Authentication Failures
178: - Ensure credentials are accessible
179: - Check token permissions
180: - Verify redirect URIs
181: 
182: ### Performance Problems
183: - Enable caching headers
184: - Use CDN for static assets
185: - Monitor memory usage
186: 
187: See [Troubleshooting Guide](troubleshooting.md) for more solutions.
</file>

