   1: # Schema.org Type Alignment - Implementation Guide
   2: ## Phase 1: CalendarEvent → Event Mapping
   3: 
   4: **Project**: bot-army-google-calendar-mcp
   5: **Phase**: 1 (Foundation)
   6: **Duration**: 4 days
   7: **Effort**: 32 developer hours
   8: **Status**: Ready to implement
   9: **Target Completion**: Week of 2026-03-31
  10: 
  11: ---
  12: 
  13: ## 📋 Document Purpose
  14: 
  15: This guide provides **step-by-step implementation instructions** for developers to align Google Calendar MCP types with schema.org vocabulary. Phase 1 focuses on core calendar operations (CalendarEvent → Event) which delivers 50% of the overall alignment benefits in minimal time.
  16: 
  17: **Audience**: Backend developers, API engineers
  18: **Prerequisites**: Familiarity with TypeScript, Google Calendar API, MCP protocol
  19: **Success Criteria**: All Phase 1 items complete with tests passing, no breaking changes
  20: 
  21: ---
  22: 
  23: ## Table of Contents
  24: 
  25: 1. [Architecture Overview](#architecture-overview)
  26: 2. [Pre-Implementation Setup](#pre-implementation-setup)
  27: 3. [Day 1: Analysis & Planning](#day-1-analysis--planning)
  28: 4. [Day 2: Core Mapping Implementation](#day-2-core-mapping-implementation)
  29: 5. [Day 3: JSON-LD Serialization](#day-3-jsonld-serialization)
  30: 6. [Day 4: Documentation & Testing](#day-4-documentation--testing)
  31: 7. [File-by-File Checklist](#file-by-file-checklist)
  32: 8. [Code Examples](#code-examples)
  33: 9. [Testing Strategy](#testing-strategy)
  34: 10. [Deployment & Validation](#deployment--validation)
  35: 
  36: ---
  37: 
  38: ## Architecture Overview
  39: 
  40: ### Current Data Flow
  41: ```
  42: API Request
  43:     ↓
  44: Tool Handler (e.g., CreateEventHandler)
  45:     ↓
  46: Google Calendar API Call
  47:     ↓
  48: Response (CalendarEvent interface)
  49:     ↓
  50: API Response (JSON)
  51:     ↓
  52: Client
  53: ```
  54: 
  55: ### Post-Implementation Data Flow
  56: ```
  57: API Request
  58:     ↓
  59: Tool Handler (e.g., CreateEventHandler)
  60:     ↓
  61: Google Calendar API Call
  62:     ↓
  63: Response (CalendarEvent interface)
  64:     ↓
  65: Schema.org Serializer (NEW)
  66:     ↓
  67: JSON-LD Response with @context (UPDATED)
  68:     ↓
  69: Client
  70: ```
  71: 
  72: ### What's NOT Changing
  73: - ✅ Internal TypeScript types (CalendarEvent, etc.) - No changes needed
  74: - ✅ Handler logic - No changes needed
  75: - ✅ Google Calendar API calls - No changes needed
  76: - ✅ Existing API contracts - Backward compatible
  77: 
  78: ### What IS Changing
  79: - ✨ Response serialization - Add JSON-LD context
  80: - ✨ API examples - Include @context and @type
  81: - ✨ Documentation - Reference schema.org types
  82: - ✨ Test fixtures - Include schema.org validation
  83: 
  84: ---
  85: 
  86: ## Pre-Implementation Setup
  87: 
  88: ### Prerequisites Checklist
  89: 
  90: - [x] Read SCHEMA-ORG-QUICK-REFERENCE.md (20 min)
  91: - [x] Read SCHEMA-ORG-ALIGNMENT.md sections 1-4 (40 min)
  92: - [ ] Install schema.org validator: https://validator.schema.org/
  93: - [ ] Set up local environment:
  94:   ```bash
  95:   cd ~/code/is-internal/bot-army-google-calendar-mcp
  96:   npm install
  97:   npm run build
  98:   npm test  # Should pass
  99:   ```
 100: 
 101: ### Key Files to Review
 102: 1. `src/schemas/types.ts` - Type definitions
 103: 2. `src/handlers/core/CreateEventHandler.ts` - Example handler
 104: 3. `src/tools/registry.ts` - Tool definitions
 105: 4. `src/index.ts` - Server entry point
 106: 5. `README.md` - API documentation
