 121: 
 122: ## Day 1: Analysis & Planning
 123: 
 124: **Goal**: Understand codebase structure, identify integration points, create detailed implementation plan
 125: 
 126: ### Morning (2 hours)
 127: 
 128: #### 1.1 Map Response Flows (45 min)
 129: 
 130: For each major tool, trace the response path:
 131: 
 132: ```typescript
 133: // Example: create-event tool
 134: 
 135: // 1. Handler file
 136: src/handlers/core/CreateEventHandler.ts
 137:   - Input: CreateEventInput
 138:   - Output: CalendarEvent (from Google Calendar API)
 139: 
 140: // 2. Registry entry
 141: src/tools/registry.ts
 142:   - Tool name: "create-event"
 143:   - Tool description
 144:   - Input schema
 145:   - Output schema (currently returns raw CalendarEvent)
 146: 
 147: // 3. Server entry point
 148: src/index.ts
 149:   - How handlers are invoked
 150:   - How responses are serialized and returned
 151: ```
 152: 
 153: **Task**: Create `docs/RESPONSE-FLOW-MAP.md` documenting:
 154: - Tool name
 155: - Handler file path
 156: - Input type
 157: - Output type (current)
 158: - Serialization point
 159: - Example current response
 160: 
 161: **Priority handlers**:
 162: - `create-event` (CreateEventHandler)
 163: - `update-event` (UpdateEventHandler)
 164: - `get-event` (GetEventHandler)
 165: - `list-events` (ListEventsHandler)
 166: - `search-events` (SearchEventsHandler)
 167: 
 168: #### 1.2 Identify Serialization Points (45 min)
 169: 
 170: Find where responses are currently serialized to JSON:
 171: 
 172: ```bash
 173: # Search for JSON serialization
 174: grep -r "JSON.stringify\|response\|return {" src/handlers/core/ | grep -v test | head -20
 175: grep -r "export.*Handler\|handle(" src/handlers/core/ | head -20
 176: ```
 177: 
 178: Look for:
 179: - Response object construction
 180: - Error handling
 181: - Field filtering
 182: - Type conversions
 183: 
 184: **Create**: `docs/SERIALIZATION-POINTS.md` with:
 185: - File paths where serialization occurs
 186: - Current serialization logic
 187: - Where to add @context injection
 188: - How to preserve backward compatibility
 189: 
 190: ### Afternoon (2 hours)
 191: 
 192: #### 1.3 Create Detailed Property Mapping (1 hour)
 193: 
 194: For CalendarEvent, create exhaustive property mapping:
 195: 
 196: ```markdown
 197: | CalendarEvent Field | schema.org Event Property | Conversion Logic | Notes |
 198: |---|---|---|---|
 199: | id | identifier | 1:1 | Direct string mapping |
 200: | summary | name | 1:1 | Direct string mapping |
 201: | start.dateTime | startDate | Convert + timezone | See timezone handling |
 202: | start.date | startDate | All-day event format | ISO 8601 date |
 203: | start.timeZone | startDate suffix | Add UTC offset | e.g., -07:00 |
 204: | end.dateTime | endDate | Convert + timezone | Must match start TZ |
 205: | end.date | endDate | All-day event format | ISO 8601 date |
 206: | location | location | String or Place object | Plain text is OK |
 207: | attendees[] | attendee[] | Map to Person objects | See Person mapping |
 208: | colorId | color | Map to color name | "blue", "red", etc. |
 209: | description | description | 1:1 | Direct string mapping |
 210: | htmlLink | url | 1:1 | Event URL |
 211: | reminders[] | reminder | Custom extension | TODO: Phase 2 |
 212: ```
 213: 
 214: **Create**: `docs/PROPERTY-MAPPING.md` with:
 215: - Complete CalendarEvent → Event property mapping
 216: - Conversion logic for each property
 217: - Timezone handling strategy
 218: - Missing property notes
 219: 
 220: #### 1.4 Design Serialization Strategy (1 hour)
 221: 
 222: Create architecture for schema.org serialization:
 223: 
 224: **Option A: Serializer Class** (Recommended)
 225: ```typescript
 226: // src/services/SchemaOrgSerializer.ts
 227: export class SchemaOrgSerializer {
 228:   serializeEvent(event: CalendarEvent): SchemaOrgEvent {
 229:     return {
 230:       "@context": "https://schema.org",
 231:       "@type": "Event",
 232:       identifier: event.id,
 233:       name: event.summary,
 234:       // ... more mappings
 235:     };
 236:   }
 237: 
 238:   serializeEvents(events: CalendarEvent[]): SchemaOrgEvent[] {
 239:     return events.map(e => this.serializeEvent(e));
