  1: # Google Calendar & Gmail MCP Server
  2: 
  3: A Model Context Protocol (MCP) server that provides Google Calendar and Gmail integration for AI assistants like Claude.
  4: 
  5: ## Features
  6: 
  7: ### Calendar
  8: - **Multi-Calendar Support**: List events from multiple calendars simultaneously
  9: - **Event Management**: Create, update, delete, and search calendar events
 10: - **Recurring Events**: Advanced modification capabilities for recurring events
 11: - **Free/Busy Queries**: Check availability across calendars
 12: - **Smart Scheduling**: Natural language understanding for dates and times
 13: - **Inteligent Import**: Add calendar events from images, PDFs or web links
 14: 
 15: ### Gmail
 16: - **Message Search**: Query Gmail with flexible search filters (is:unread, from:, subject:, etc.)
 17: - **Profile Management**: Get account information (message count, thread count, email address)
 18: - **Multi-Account Support**: Use multiple Gmail accounts with separate OAuth tokens
 19: 
 20: ## Recent Updates (v1.4.9)
 21: 
 22: **Performance & Reliability:**
 23: - 🚀 Dynamic label ID resolution (L6) - Scripts now work across accounts with different label hierarchies
 24: - ⚡ Sequential API optimization - ~500ms latency reduction per operation
 25: - 📦 Batch filter operations - 10-100x speedup for bulk Gmail tasks
 26: - 🔧 Timezone utilities consolidation - Reduced codebase by 19 lines, eliminated duplicate datetime logic
 27: 
 28: **Tooling & Infrastructure:**
 29: - ✅ Comprehensive label resolution guide ([docs/LABEL-RESOLUTION-GUIDE.md](docs/LABEL-RESOLUTION-GUIDE.md))
 30: - 🧪 Parametrized test expansion (25 → 30+ test cases)
 31: - 📋 New changelog system ([docs/changelog/](docs/changelog/)) tracking all improvements
 32: - 🔐 Auth refactor: new `isAuthenticated()` and `getCredentials()` methods
 33: 
 34: **Testing:**
 35: - 486/486 tests passing (100%) ✅
 36: - Integration tests for conflict detection via MCP protocol (real server, real API)
 37: - Reduced technical debt with shared utilities in `lib/gmail-*.mjs`
 38: - CLAUDE.md updated with latest patterns and utilities
 39: 
 40: See [CHANGELOG](docs/CHANGELOG.md) for complete v1.4.9 release notes.
 41: 
 42: ## Quick Start
 43: 
 44: ### Prerequisites
 45: 
 46: 1. A Google Cloud project with the Calendar API enabled
 47: 2. OAuth 2.0 credentials (Desktop app type)
 48: 
 49: ### Google Cloud Setup
 50: 
 51: 1. Go to the [Google Cloud Console](https://console.cloud.google.com)
 52: 2. Create a new project or select an existing one.
 53: 3. Enable the [Google Calendar API](https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/library/calendar-json.googleapis.com) for your project. Ensure that the right project is selected from the top bar before enabling the API.
 54: 4. Create OAuth 2.0 credentials:
 55:    - Go to Credentials
 56:    - Click "Create Credentials" > "OAuth client ID"
 57:    - Choose "User data" for the type of data that the app will be accessing
 58:    - Add your app name and contact information
 59:    - Add the following scopes (optional):
 60:      - `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar.events` and `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar`
 61:    - Select "Desktop app" as the application type (Important!)
 62:    - Save the auth key, you'll need to add its path to the JSON in the next step
 63:    - Add your email address as a test user under the [Audience screen](https://console.cloud.google.com/auth/audience)
 64:       - Note: it might take a few minutes for the test user to be added. The OAuth consent will not allow you to proceed until the test user has propagated.
 65:       - Note about test mode: While an app is in test mode the auth tokens will expire after 1 week and need to be refreshed (see Re-authentication section below).
 66: 
 67: ### Installation
 68: 
 69: **Option 1: Use with npx (Recommended)**
 70: 
 71: Add to your Claude Desktop configuration:
 72: 
 73: **macOS**: `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json`
 74: **Windows**: `%APPDATA%\Claude\claude_desktop_config.json`
 75: ```json
 76: {
 77:   "mcpServers": {
 78:     "google-calendar": {
 79:       "command": "npx",
 80:       "args": ["@cocal/google-calendar-mcp"],
 81:       "env": {
 82:         "GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS": "/path/to/your/gcp-oauth.keys.json"
 83:       }
 84:     }
 85:   }
 86: }
 87: ```
 88: 
 89: **⚠️ Important Note for npx Users**: When using npx, you **must** specify the credentials file path using the `GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS` environment variable.
 90: 
 91: **Option 2: Local Installation**
 92: 
 93: ```bash
 94: git clone https://github.com/nspady/google-calendar-mcp.git
 95: cd google-calendar-mcp
 96: npm install
 97: npm run build
 98: ```
 99: 
100: Then add to Claude Desktop config using the local path or by specifying the path with the `GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS` environment variable.
101: 
102: ### First Run
103: 
104: 1. Start Claude Desktop
105: 2. The server will prompt for authentication on first use
106: 3. Complete the OAuth flow in your browser
107: 4. You're ready to use calendar features!
108: 
109: ### Multi-Account Support (Test Mode)
110: 
111: This server supports multiple Google accounts in test mode with automatic token management.
112: 
113: **Setup both accounts:**
114: 
115: Account 1 (Initial):
116: ```bash
117: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
118: export CALENDARMCP_TOKEN_PATH=~/.config/google-calendar-mcp/tokens.json
119: npm run auth
120: ```
121: 
122: Account 2 (Same file, different account key):
123: ```bash
124: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
125: export CALENDARMCP_TOKEN_PATH=~/.config/google-calendar-mcp/tokens.json
126: npm run auth  # Authenticates second account in same tokens.json
127: ```
128: 
129: **Verify both accounts:**
130: ```bash
131: export GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS="./credentials.json"
132: npm run verify-tokens
133: ```
134: 
135: Outputs token status, expiry times, and account validity for all authenticated accounts.
136: 
137: **Important Notes:**
138: - Both accounts stored in single `tokens.json` file with separate keys
139: - Tokens expire after 7 days in test mode (Google requirement)
140: - TokenManager auto-refreshes tokens 5 minutes before expiry
141: - Set `ACCOUNT_MODE` environment variable before running the server to select which account is active
142: 
143: ### Re-authentication
144: 
145: If you're in test mode (default), tokens expire after 7 days. If you are using a client like Claude Desktop it should open up a browser window to automatically re-auth. However, if you see authentication errors you can also resolve by following these steps:
146: 
147: **For npx users:**
148: ```bash
149: export GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS="/path/to/your/gcp-oauth.keys.json"
150: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
151: npx @cocal/google-calendar-mcp auth
152: ```
153: 
154: **For local installation:**
155: ```bash
156: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
157: npm run auth
158: ```
159: 
160: **To avoid weekly re-authentication**, publish your app to production mode (without verification):
161: 1. Go to Google Cloud Console → "APIs & Services" → "OAuth consent screen"
162: 2. Click "PUBLISH APP" and confirm
163: 3. Your tokens will no longer expire after 7 days but Google will show a more threatning warning when connecting to the app about it being unverified.
164: 
165: See [Authentication Guide](docs/authentication.md#moving-to-production-mode-recommended) for details.
166: 
167: ### Gmail OAuth Setup
168: 
169: To enable Gmail features, authenticate with Gmail scopes:
170: 
171: ```bash
172: # Using the provided auth script
173: node auth-gmail.mjs
174: ```
175: 
176: This will:
177: 1. Open your browser for OAuth authentication
178: 2. Request Gmail access (read and modify permissions)
179: 3. Save tokens to `~/.config/google-calendar-mcp/tokens-gmail.json`
180: 
181: **Quick Check:**
182: ```bash
183: # Check unread message count
184: node check-gmail.mjs
185: ```
186: 
187: **Important Notes:**
188: - Gmail and Calendar tokens are stored separately
189: - Gmail scopes: `gmail.readonly`, `gmail.modify`
190: - Tokens expire after 7 days in test mode
191: - Re-authenticate as needed with `node auth-gmail.mjs`
192: 
193: ### Email Organization & Filtering Scripts
194: 
195: Automated scripts for organizing and filtering large volumes of Gmail with focus on correctness and efficiency.
196: 
197: **Management Scripts:** (use shared `createGmailClient()` for OAuth, error handling, and multi-account support)
198: - `list-unread-emails.mjs` - Categorize and summarize unread emails by label/sender patterns; clean fallback categorization
199: - `summarize-remaining.mjs` - Summary of uncategorized/remaining unread emails (internal work, forums, misc); parallel fetching
200: - `describe-internal.mjs` - Detailed breakdown of internal team emails with subjects and dates; hardcoded summary removed
201: - `apply-filters-to-unread.mjs` - Apply existing filters to current unread emails
202: - `create-remaining-filters.mjs` - Batch create filters for multiple categories (Product Updates, Communities, Services)
203: 
204: **Specialized Filters:**
205: - `create-billing-filter.mjs` - Smart billing filter with conditional rate-limit detection
206: - `create-signoz-filter.mjs` - Archive SigNoz monitoring alerts automatically
207: - `create-dmarc-filter.mjs` - Organize DMARC authentication reports
208: - `create-eventbrite-filter.mjs` - Label and archive Eventbrite event emails
209: - `create-meet-notes-filter.mjs` - Label Google Meet notes
210: - `delete-sentry-filter.mjs` - Remove outdated filters
211: 
212: **Archive & Processing Scripts:**
213: - `archive-signoz-dmarc.mjs` - Batch archive monitoring and DMARC report emails using Gmail batch API
214: - `mark-signoz-read.mjs` - Mark SigNoz alerts as read in bulk
215: - `mark-past-events-read.mjs` - Classify event emails by date and mark past events as read
216: - `protect-important-inbox.mjs` - Label critical items to prevent archiving (payments, rate limits, services)
217: 
218: **Event Management:**
219: - `filter-events-by-date.mjs` - Classify event emails as future (label + keep) or past (label + archive)
220: - `organize-international-house.mjs` - Label and organize International House event emails
221: 
222: **Utilities:**
223: - `lib/gmail-client.mjs` - Authenticated Gmail API client factory. Centralizes OAuth2 init, token validation, and multi-account support:
224:   ```js
225:   import { createGmailClient } from './lib/gmail-client.mjs';
226:   const gmail = createGmailClient(); // Uses ACCOUNT_MODE env var, throws on missing tokens
227:   ```
228: - `lib/gmail-label-utils.mjs` - Label ID resolution (NEW in v1.4.9). Resolves hardcoded label IDs dynamically for account portability:
229:   ```js
230:   import { buildLabelCache, resolveLabelId } from './lib/gmail-label-utils.mjs';
231:   const labelCache = await buildLabelCache(gmail);
232:   const labelId = labelCache.get('Events/Community'); // Dynamic instead of hardcoded Label_N
233:   ```
234:   See [`docs/LABEL-RESOLUTION-GUIDE.md`](docs/LABEL-RESOLUTION-GUIDE.md) for complete documentation.
235: - `lib/gmail-batch.mjs` - Batch filter operations for bulk Gmail tasks (10-100x speedup)
236: - `lib/date-based-filter.mjs` - Pure utility for date-based email classification: extracts dates (ISO, US format, text dates, weekday patterns), compares to today, classifies as past/future/unknown. Does not mutate input. Handles dates without year by inferring current or next year.
237: 
238: ## Example Usage
239: 
240: Along with the normal capabilities you would expect for a calendar integration you can also do really dynamic, multi-step processes like:
241: 
242: 1. **Cross-calendar availability**:
243:    ```
244:    Please provide availability looking at both my personal and work calendar for this upcoming week.
245:    I am looking for a good time to meet with someone in London for 1 hr.
246:    ```
247: 
248: 2. Add events from screenshots, images and other data sources:
249:    ```
250:    Add this event to my calendar based on the attached screenshot.
251:    ```
252:    Supported image formats: PNG, JPEG, GIF
253:    Images can contain event details like date, time, location, and description
254: 
255: 3. Calendar analysis:
256:    ```
257:    What events do I have coming up this week that aren't part of my usual routine?
258:    ```
259: 4. Check attendance:
260:    ```
261:    Which events tomorrow have attendees who have not accepted the invitation?
262:    ```
263: 5. Auto coordinate events:
264:    ```
265:    Here's some available that was provided to me by someone. {available times}
266:    Take a look at the times provided and let me know which ones are open on my calendar.
267:    ```
268: 
269: 6. **Gmail workflows**:
270:    ```
271:    How many unread emails do I have from my work account?
272:    ```
273:    ```
274:    Search for all emails from john@company.com that I haven't replied to yet.
275:    ```
276:    ```
277:    Show me all unread messages from the past week.
278:    ```
279:    ```
280:    Mark all unread emails from my boss as read.
281:    ```
282:    ```
283:    Archive all promotional emails from marketing.
284:    ```
285:    ```
286:    Delete these 5 spam messages (provide IDs).
287:    ```
288: 
289: ## Date Parsing
290: 
291: The email organization system uses intelligent date parsing (`lib/date-based-filter.mjs`) to classify event emails:
292: 
293: **Supported Formats:**
294: - ISO 8601: `2026-03-25`, `2026/03/25`
295: - US format: `03/25/2026`, `3/25/2026`
296: - Text format: `March 25, 2026`, `March 25` (infers year)
297: - Weekday patterns: `@ Mon, Mar 23`, `@ Friday Mar 22`
298: - Returns `null` for unparseable dates
299: 
300: **Classification:**
301: - Past events (date < today): archive from inbox, keep label
302: - Future events (date ≥ today): label and keep in inbox
303: - Unknown: marked for manual review
304: 
305: **Implementation Notes:**
306: - Pure function: does not mutate input dates
307: - Handles missing years by inferring current or next year
308: - Used by `mark-past-events-read.mjs` to auto-archive old events
309: 
